values:
SO YOU THINK we have no culture
You think we can learn our culture
by walking through museums...
Denial. You're in denial.
You can't see what we live every day.

Why does this beggar in Bangkok look lost?
he's lost his wetland culture
he's lost his way of life
his knowledge of survival.

Why do we fight Iraq and Iran and...etc.
We're fighting for our culture
Because what would we do if we couldn't have Oil.

How would we drive
How would we eat
How would our food get to our plates?
we'll have lost our way of life
our knowledge of survival.

So don't act confused when men and women
Choose to fight for their culture
As if they're fighting for fringe
Or for display cases in a carpeted room.

They're fighting for
Wetlands.

Because that's how they fish
That's how they eat
That's how they live.

We've known money and oil for
Some hundred years.
They've known fish and rice fields for
Some thousand.

Every day
We in our culture
Ask more of them in their culture

To give up their culture
Like it's easy
Like it doesn't cause violence and heartache and
hunger and death and forced sex and labor and
a deep seeded
dehumanization

The echoing sounds under a bridge
Over dead river
Can hear it for blocks of tall buildings
And litter
Past parking lots of
Rusty cars and sour smells
Empty streets empty of people
Harrison and Jefferson
Roads  called after our forefathers
Who built the foundation
For today in this nation
And this nation
Of course it ain't nothin
But good
Enough
Yellow signs speckled brown
Wanna write it all down
And then get myself on a greyhound
Out of this town
Out of this town

Today was Sumer's birthday.  I wrote her a letter that I can't really show anyone.  But I might print it and bury it next to her some day.  And I spent the rest of the day packing up boxes.

oooooooooh, so how do I feel.  I miss everyone so much, and I almost just want to cancel all my Thailand plans and settle down on one of the coasts and become an artist, selling random things on the street, maybe having a job as a waitress on the side.  Hanging out with friends at night.  Friends who understand where I'm at more than I do and who I would do anything for.

But I have to go...I've been looking forward to going back for so long.  And this time will be different, but I'm going to learn so much about how to be.  1 year.  And then I'll have a niece AND a nephew.  Everyone will be 1 year older.  Life here will have changed.  I will have changed.  Life will go on.  My heart will break at leaving Thailand.  I'll feel strange in my own country...really strange.  I'll choose a state to live in.  And I'll live.  Maybe I'll bring home a Thai husband and daughter.  haha no.

I sort of think I'm ready to go to therepy.  That's good.  I haven't been ready to talk in a long time...ever?  Whatever.

I'm studying econ.  My last final of college: econ.  What ze hell.

I guess I don't know how to feel right now.  But have I ever?

My friends have been floating away, one by one earlier than expected.  In a week and half all of them will.  I'll be floating, too, but not with them.  Oh friends, I miss you.  :S

Ok.  Time to read more about money.

"Who gave them out, whence they last came, where they began, through what agency they crookedly quivered and jerked, scores at a time, over the heads of the crowd, like a kind of lightning, no eye in the throng could have told; but, muskets were being distributed -- so were cartridges, powder, and ball, bars of iron and wood, knives, axes , pikes, every weapon that distracted ingenuity could discover or devise.  People who could lay hold of nothing else, set themselves with bleeding hands to force stones and bricks out of their places in walls.  Every pulse and heart in Saint Antoine was on high-fever strain and at high-fever heat.  Every living creature there held life as of no account, and was demented with a passionate readiness to sacrifice it." - Charles Dickens, A Tale of Two Cities

Preceded by intense description of Hunger and Want.  Foreshadowed by red wine-stained hands that turn into blood stains and birds oblivous to heads dropping off in the future.
La Revolution Francaise.

Dear Representative Timothy Johnson,
The recent news about Israel and Lebanon has been heartbreaking, and I am ashamed I have not written to you before today.
Hezbollah and other terrorist organizations have caused turmoil in the Middle East and much of the rest of the world.  However, invading Lebanon because its government is too weak to subdue or destroy Hezbollah is not only inhumane and unjust to the families and friends of the killed and wounded civilians in Lebanon, it is unwise.
I realize that peace talks, cease-fires, and international armies all seem hopeless right now, but I must disagree that they do less to addressing the root of the violence between terrorist organizations and Israel, than does leaving and/or helping Israel to bomb a country and its civilians indiscriminantly.
I ask that you actively support a cease-fire and/or an international presence in Lebanon and Israel.  Above all, please do not support sending more weapons to Israel.
Thank you for your time,
Vanessa Moll
